Create a method that encapsulates the duplicated code:

     string LetterFromGrade(int grade)
     {
         if (grade &gt; 79) return &quot;A&quot;;
         if (grade &gt; 69) return &quot;B&quot;;
         ...
     }

And then use that method everywhere.

     labelGrade1.Text = LetterFromGrade(grade1);
     labelGrade2.Text = LetterFromGrade(grade2);
     ...

You can refactor your code like this:

    Action&lt;int, Label&gt; updateLabel = (value, label) =&gt;
    {
      if ( value &gt;= 80 )
        label.Text = &quot;A&quot;;
      else
      if ( value &gt;= 70 )
        label.Text = &quot;B&quot;;
    };

    updateLabel (grade1, labelGrade1);
    updateLabel (grade2, labelGrade2);

Better smell.

You can of course create a class method instead of an local but if it is only used in a method, local is better as a class method allows other code to call it while this code is not intended for them.

